#limitation(title: [NIH Deep Phenotyping Study: Small Sample and Contested Interpretation])[
The Walitt et al.\ 2024 study is the most comprehensive deep-phenotyping study of ME/CFS to date, but its conclusions are constrained by design limitations:

    - The study enrolled only 17 post-infectious ME/CFS patients against an original target of 40; recruitment was halted due to COVID-19. At n=17 vs.\ 21 controls, many comparisons are underpowered and findings may not generalize.
    - Severe and very severe patients were excluded because they could not travel to the NIH Clinical Center—the population with the most extreme pathophysiology is systematically absent.
    - The use of “effort preference” to describe grip strength findings generated legitimate scientific controversy; whether the framing reflects unconscious neural computation (as the authors clarified) or introduces psychologizing bias into objective data remains unresolved.
    - Biological findings (CSF catecholamine deficiency, B cell shifts, autonomic dysfunction) are unreplicated by independent groups and derive from a single cross-sectional assessment.

]
